# Testing

## Frontend setup (Vitest)

- Runner: **Vitest** (Vite-native unit testing)
- Environment: `jsdom`
- Globals: enabled (`describe`, `it`, `expect`, `beforeEach` etc. — no imports needed)
- Setup file: `frontend/src/test/setup.ts` loads `@testing-library/jest-dom/vitest`

### Component Test Example:
```tsx
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import { Button } from '../Button';

describe('Button', () => {
  it('renders children correctly', () => {
    render(<Button>Click me</Button>);
    expect(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /click me/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

## Backend setup (Unit & Integration tests)

- Backend tests reside alongside services and utils (`backend/src/services/*.test.ts`).
- Uses custom assertion methods. Run via:
  ```bash
  npm --prefix backend run test
  ```

## What to test

- **Frontend:** Component renders, loading/error states, user interactions (click, inputs), form validators, and CSV/XLSX parser logic.
- **Backend:** Data transformations, sheet column mapping conversions, JWT signature mockings, integration callback messages, and database seeding states.
- Avoid writing snapshot tests due to low signal-to-noise.
